releases.title: Since I Left You
releases.label: XL Recordings
releases.notes:
This is the 2016 reissue on XL Recordings, domestic to UK and Europe. 

All barcodes, matrices, stamper codes, and labels are identical to those of the 2012 reissue on XL recordings.  Runouts are stamped.

It is only distinguishable by its inner sleeves: those of the 2016 reissue were white, as opposed to the black of the 2012 issue. 

-The back sleeve lists "Bobby Dazzler Productions", "Modular", "XL Recordings"
-The websites "www.modularpeople.com" and "xlrecordings" are printed above the barcode
-The gatefold contains an extensive sample list on the right-hand panel
-Track C2/11 is listed as "Tonight" on the sleeve, but "Tonight May Have To Last Me All My Life" on the side C label
-The gatefold spine is blue
-The inner sleeves are white
-The XL and Modular logos and websites are printed on sides A,B,C, and D labels; there are no white rings bordering the labels

Sample notes:
-Uses the ORIGINAL SAMPLES version of "Frontier Psychiatrist" 

FOOTNOTE
The following is true for every vinyl pressing of "Since I Left You" (except the Rex Records test pressing):
"Since I Left You" and "Live At Dominoes" do not contain the "younger than springtime" sample from Rodgers/Hammerstein.
"Summer Crane" and "Extra Kings" do not contain the flute sample from War's "H2Overture"
"Radio" does not contain the "Johnny!" dialogue at the beginning
"Diners Only" does not contain the "good evening gentlemen" dialogue at the beginning

releases.notes:
Cat # on back sleeve is SCR 488209 2. On spine 448209 2 and CRECD 196.

In Norway, release came out with a large yellow hype sticker on front of the jewel case.

Standard jewel case with clear tray including 12-page booklet:
- no lyrics but several photos shot by [a2234476] around the Scottish Highlands during a three-day road trip in spring 1997:

the original press release for the album details the trip: "They visited the nuclear power station at Torness, saw the funfair being dismantled at Aviemore and played a round of golf under the gaze of Ben Nevis. It didn't rain once."

- tracklisting, band members/guests/instruments, thanks, album credits including production/engineering/mixing & other informations:

Recorded at Ridge Farm May 20 to July 10, 1996, and at Air Studios December 1 - 7, 1996, & February 3 - 8, 1997. Strings and brass recorded at Abbey Road, June 16, 1996. Mixed January 12 - 24 & February 3 - 8, 1997.

Album title:
The band has described it as "a joking reference to Britpop, and everybody who thought we were part of that scene".
[a264177] added in 2016 "We just thought it sounded funny. No one calls Scotland "Northern Britain," although technically it is."

CHEMICAL BROTHERS Further Deluxe Edition 2-disc [CD/DVD] album set - Further is the Chemical Brothers seventh studio album an eight track masterpiece of modern psychedelia. Effortlessly fusing freefrom analogue wig-outs to juggernaut dancefloor dynamics the record sees Tom Rowlands & Ed Simons explore the boundless possibilities of their sound.
